<br>
Its not that the design of monks changed over time, its that what they were designed around (for this issue) changed.  <br>
<br>
-Monks were given a weight limit to stop them from using the better armor, which was usually of the heavier variety. <br>
<br>
-Monks were restricted to leather, which is one of the worst armors out there.<br>
<br>
Combine those two points and you have a fairly decent way to let the gear that monks can reasonably use determine their defense, rather then making it totally a part of themselves..like warriors.  <br>
<br>
That was the whole defensive balancing crux for monks.  A combination of weight limit restrictions and class restrictions kept their defensive abilities in balance....<br>
<br>
Then what happened?  Velious came along and you got all/all gear that was far superior to what monks *should* have been able to get defensively.  It was all low weight, high hp/ac, all/all gear...<br>
<br>
So, while the punishments are still in place...restrictions and weight limits..they are made almost null and void because they are so easily bypassed.  <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Now-The best way to &quot;fix&quot; the problem would have been to remove monk  as an option for alot of that gear...or raise the weight.  That way the gear falls back in line with the restrictions and the monk, as a class, remains as it always has been.  But, that would have been far too time consuming...and about every monk in the game would lose the ability to wear half their gear overnight...so the only viable solution was to nerf the monks ability to use that uber gear.  <br>
<br>
<br>
As for your other arguments, about no one ever using a monk for tanking... monks were used over plate classes for rampage tanks more often then not.  Yes, perhaps some of the lower end raiding monks weren't outright tanking uber mobs, but they were taking the place of other tank classes in that capacity.  <br>
<br>
That and monks really aren't that hurting over this.  Most of them are doing more then fine these days.  They are just back to their old roles...pulling and damage.  And realistically, damage stacks, it doesn't matter if you are 5 or 10% worse then the &quot;best damage class&quot; , you are still a very viable option.  No guild can afford to have a straight up army of only rogue damage dealers.. Imagine the competition for the loot, everyone wanting the exact same gear.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   It would be a nightmare.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   So yeah, it is in a guild's best interest to diversify its damage dealers even if they aren't exactly top dog.  Because, realistically..there can be only one &quot;best&quot; and that doesn't negate what other classes can bring.  <br>
<br>
Yeah...Imaging trying to gear up 20 rogues to move on to the next encounter, each encounter.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=arothtb>Aroth TB</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 18<br> <font color=#333333>(2/21/03 10:12:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8828.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_cry.gif" align=absmiddle>  .</span><hr size=1> As always it's easy to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>say</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> anything when it's not <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>your</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> class.<br>
